SUMMARY:Litigating Faculty First Amendment Rights
DESCRIPTION:Surprisingly\, up until recently it was unclear whether facul
 ty members at public universities had any First Amendment rights related 
 to their teaching. The law continues to evolve in the federal courts. Thi
 s program will feature a Chicago-based law professor\, Jason Kilborn\, wh
 o litigated and won an important\, precedent-setting holding in 2025 from
  the Seventh Circuit US Court of Appeals (which also covers Indiana) that
  faculty members do have First Amendment rights for their academic speech
 .  Professor Kilborn will be in conversation with Maurer Professor Steve 
 Sanders\, an expert on the law of academic freedom\, and Maurer alumnus J
 osh Bleisch\, who has litigated similar cases for FIRE and the ACLU of In
 diana.&#160\;  RSVP below by 10 am on Saturday\, March 28 to attend. Food
  will be provided to those who RSVP.&#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  Surprisingly\, up until recently it was
  unclear whether faculty members at public universities had any First Ame
 ndment rights related to their teaching. The law continues to evolve in t
 he federal courts. This program will feature a Chicago-based law professo
 r\, Jason Kilborn\, who litigated and won an important\, precedent-settin
 g holding in 2025 from the Seventh Circuit US Court of Appeals (which als
 o covers Indiana) that faculty members <em>do</em> have First Amendment r
 ights for their academic speech.</p><p>  Professor Kilborn will be in con
 versation with Maurer Professor Steve Sanders\, an expert on the law of a
 cademic freedom\, and Maurer alumnus Josh Bleisch\, who has litigated sim
 ilar cases for FIRE and the ACLU of Indiana.&#160\;</p><p>  RSVP below by
  10 am on Saturday\, March 28 to attend. Food will be provided to those w
 ho RSVP.&#160\;</p>
